         <abstract>
            <p>Gerard Noiriel's recent book, Sur la "crise" de l'histoire (Paris, 1996), describes a social and intellectual crisis of fragmentation among contemporary professional historians and then proposes to restore professional unities through a disciplinary commitment to pragmatic ideas and methods. According to Noiriel, social inequalities within the profession and a recent turn toward postmodern, philosophical skepticism have undermined professional unity and the traditional paradigm of historical knowledge. In response to these perceived threats, Noiriel advocates a pragmatic philosophy that will help historians recognize the practices and language they share. Yet Noiriel's pragmatic quest for a professional paradigm offers few solutions for the profession's social stratifications, and his pragmatism remains as dependent on philosophy as the historical theories he condemns. There are nevertheless intriguing ironies in Noiriel's use of an American philosophy to criticize recent American uses of French theories.</p>
         </abstract>
